There's no volatility
of the first asset.

00:36:14.170 --> 00:36:15.760
So that's cash, OK?

00:36:15.760 --> 00:36:19.240
So that's a riskless
asset in the first one.

00:36:19.240 --> 00:36:22.740
So let's even call that
R_1 is less than R_2.

00:36:22.740 --> 00:36:24.530
So that's the-- right?

00:36:24.530 --> 00:36:28.170
You have the cash asset, and
then you have a non-cash asset.

00:36:28.170 --> 00:36:30.539
Rho equal to 0,
zero correlation.

00:36:30.539 --> 00:36:32.330
So let's look at what
this line looks like.

00:36:54.400 --> 00:36:58.971
So R_1, R_2, sigma_2 here.

00:36:58.971 --> 00:37:06.450
When you weight asset
two 100%, you're

00:37:06.450 --> 00:37:08.490
going to get this point, right?

00:37:08.490 --> 00:37:15.020
When you weight asset
one 100%, you're

00:37:15.020 --> 00:37:17.940
going to get this point, right?

00:37:17.940 --> 00:37:24.440
So what's in the
middle of your return

00:37:24.440 --> 00:37:27.510
as a function of variance?

00:37:27.510 --> 00:37:30.500
Can someone guess?

00:37:30.500 --> 00:37:31.824
AUDIENCE: A parabola?

00:37:31.824 --> 00:37:33.640
Should it be a parabola?

00:37:33.640 --> 00:37:35.655
PROFESSOR: Try again.

00:37:35.655 --> 00:37:36.530
AUDIENCE: A parabola.

00:37:36.530 --> 00:37:37.890
PROFESSOR: Yeah, I know, I know.

00:37:37.890 --> 00:37:38.665
Thank you.

00:37:38.665 --> 00:37:40.270
Are there any other answers?

00:37:45.640 --> 00:37:47.540
OK, this is actually
I-- let me just

00:37:47.540 --> 00:37:50.140
derive very quickly for you.

00:37:50.140 --> 00:37:52.736
Sigma_1 equal to
0, rho equal to 0.

00:37:52.736 --> 00:37:53.360
What's sigma_P?

00:38:03.080 --> 00:38:05.240
Right?

00:38:05.240 --> 00:38:16.780
And sigma_P is essentially
proportional to sigma_2

00:38:16.780 --> 00:38:19.750
with the weighting.

00:38:19.750 --> 00:38:21.914
OK, and what's R?

00:38:26.090 --> 00:38:30.130
R is a linear combination
of R_1 and R_2.

00:38:30.130 --> 00:38:37.190
So it's still-- so it's linear.

00:38:41.770 --> 00:38:47.060
OK, so because in these
cases, you actually-- you

00:38:47.060 --> 00:38:52.220
essentially-- your return
is a linear function.

00:38:52.220 --> 00:38:55.000
And the slope, what
is the slope of this?

00:39:00.620 --> 00:39:02.410
Oh, let's wait on the slope.

00:39:02.410 --> 00:39:04.060
So we can come back to this.

00:39:04.060 --> 00:39:09.080
This actually relates back to
the so-called capital market

00:39:09.080 --> 00:39:12.515
line or capital
allocation line, OK?

00:39:12.515 --> 00:39:14.890
Because last time we talked
about the efficient frontier.

00:39:19.810 --> 00:39:25.450
That's when we have no riskless
assets in the portfolio, right?

00:39:25.450 --> 00:39:31.860
When you add on cash, then
you actually can select.

00:39:31.860 --> 00:39:34.990
You can combine the
cash into the portfolio

00:39:34.990 --> 00:39:42.490
by having a higher boundary,
higher Efficient Frontier,

00:39:42.490 --> 00:39:45.240
and essentially a higher
return with the same exposure.

00:39:50.370 --> 00:39:52.510
So let's look at a
couple more cases, then

00:39:52.510 --> 00:40:02.280
I will tell you-- so I
think let's look at-- so R_1

00:40:02.280 --> 00:40:04.350
is less than R_2.

00:40:04.350 --> 00:40:08.390
And volatilities are not 0.

00:40:08.390 --> 00:40:13.070
Also, sigma_1 is
less than sigma_2,

00:40:13.070 --> 00:40:28.920
but it has a negative
correlation of 1.

00:40:28.920 --> 00:40:32.660
So you'll have asset
one, asset two.

00:40:32.660 --> 00:40:38.720
And as we know, where you pick
half and half, this goes to 0.

00:40:38.720 --> 00:40:41.070
So this is a quadratic function.

00:40:41.070 --> 00:40:43.950
You can verify and
prove it later.

00:40:43.950 --> 00:40:54.830
And what if when
rho is equal to 0--

00:40:54.830 --> 00:41:02.840
and actually, I want to-- so
sigma_1 should be here, OK?

00:41:02.840 --> 00:41:06.680
So when rho is equal
to zero, this no longer

00:41:06.680 --> 00:41:10.135
goes to-- the variance can
no longer be minimized to 0.

00:41:13.920 --> 00:41:16.470
So this is your efficient
frontier, this part.

00:41:23.260 --> 00:41:27.150
I think that's enough
examples of two assets

00:41:27.150 --> 00:41:28.520
for the efficient frontier.

00:41:28.520 --> 00:41:30.080
So you get the idea.

00:41:30.080 --> 00:41:32.847
So then what if we
have three assets?

00:41:32.847 --> 00:41:34.680
So let me just touch
upon that very quickly.

00:41:34.680 --> 00:41:38.880
If you have one more
asset here, essentially

00:41:38.880 --> 00:41:41.020
you can solve the
same equations.

00:41:41.020 --> 00:41:48.770
And when the-- special case:
you can verify afterwards,

00:41:48.770 --> 00:41:50.580
if all the
volatilities are equal,

00:41:50.580 --> 00:41:54.540
and zero correlation
among the assets.

00:41:54.540 --> 00:42:00.500
You're going to be able to
minimize sigma_P equal to 1

00:42:00.500 --> 00:42:03.550
over the square root
of three of sigma_1.

00:42:03.550 --> 00:42:04.050
OK.

00:42:07.690 --> 00:42:09.050
So it seems pretty neat, right?

00:42:09.050 --> 00:42:13.100
The math is not hard
and straightforward.

00:42:13.100 --> 00:42:16.540
But it gives you the idea
how to answer your question,

00:42:16.540 --> 00:42:20.570
how to select them when
you start with two.

00:42:20.570 --> 00:42:23.580
So why are two
assets so important?

00:42:23.580 --> 00:42:26.270
What's the implication
in practice?

00:42:26.270 --> 00:42:31.230
It's actually a very
popular combination.

00:42:31.230 --> 00:42:34.180
Lot of the asset
managers, they simply

00:42:34.180 --> 00:42:38.070
benchmark to bonds
versus equity.

00:42:38.070 --> 00:42:41.290
And then one famous
combination is really 60/40.

00:42:41.290 --> 00:42:42.990
They call it a
60/40 combination.

00:42:42.990 --> 00:42:46.130
60% in equity, 40% in bonds.

00:42:46.130 --> 00:42:49.890
And even nowadays, any fund
manager, you have that.

00:42:49.890 --> 00:42:52.140
People will still ask you
to compare your performance

00:42:52.140 --> 00:42:53.170
with that combination.

00:42:53.170 --> 00:42:59.020
So the two-asset examples seem
to be quite easy and simple,

00:42:59.020 --> 00:43:05.440
but actually it's a very
important one to compare.

00:43:05.440 --> 00:43:09.700
And that will lead me to
get into the risk parity

00:43:09.700 --> 00:43:10.390
discussion.

00:43:10.390 --> 00:43:13.330
But before I get to
risk parity discussion,

00:43:13.330 --> 00:43:17.080
I want to review the concept
of beta and the Sharpe ratio.

00:44:21.530 --> 00:44:28.260
So your portfolio return,
this is your benchmark return,

00:44:28.260 --> 00:44:29.840
R of m, expected return.

00:44:29.840 --> 00:44:36.520
R_f is the risk-free return,
so essentially a cash return.

00:44:36.520 --> 00:44:41.150
And alpha is what you can
generate additionally.

00:44:41.150 --> 00:44:45.650
So let's even not to worry
about these small other terms--

00:44:45.650 --> 00:44:48.870
or not necessarily small,
but for the simplicity,

00:44:48.870 --> 00:44:50.550
I'll just reveal that.

00:44:50.550 --> 00:44:52.660
So that's your beta.

00:44:52.660 --> 00:44:53.910
Now what is your Sharpe ratio?

00:45:14.710 --> 00:45:15.330
OK.

00:45:15.330 --> 00:45:21.020
And you can-- so
sometimes Sharpe

00:45:21.020 --> 00:45:26.315
ratio is also called
risk-weighted return,

00:45:26.315 --> 00:45:30.380
or risk-adjusted return.

00:45:30.380 --> 00:45:36.670
And how many of you have
heard of Kelly's formula?

00:45:36.670 --> 00:45:39.680
So Kelly's formula
basically gives you

00:45:39.680 --> 00:45:44.460
that when you have-- let's
say in the gambling example,

00:45:44.460 --> 00:45:47.540
you know your winning
probability is p.

00:45:55.220 --> 00:45:59.600
So this basically tells
you how much to size up,

00:45:59.600 --> 00:46:01.270
how much you want to bet on.

00:46:01.270 --> 00:46:03.130
So it's a very simple formula.

00:46:07.260 --> 00:46:13.010
So you have a winning
probability of 50/50,

00:46:13.010 --> 00:46:16.300
how much you bet on?

00:46:16.300 --> 00:46:17.330
Nothing.

00:46:17.330 --> 00:46:23.850
So if you have p equal to 100%,
you bet 100% of your position.

00:46:23.850 --> 00:46:28.170
If you have a winning
probability of negative 100%,

00:46:28.170 --> 00:46:29.560
so what does it mean?

00:46:29.560 --> 00:46:32.760
That means you have a 100%
probability of losing it.

00:46:32.760 --> 00:46:34.290
What do you do?

00:46:34.290 --> 00:46:36.080
You bet the other
way around, right?

00:46:36.080 --> 00:46:40.665
You bet the other side, so that
when p is equal to negative--

00:46:40.665 --> 00:46:42.040
I'm sorry, actually
what I should

00:46:42.040 --> 00:46:46.480
say is when p equal to 0, your
losing probability becomes

00:46:46.480 --> 00:46:47.710
100%, right?

00:46:47.710 --> 00:46:51.370
So you bet 100%
the other way, OK?

00:46:51.370 --> 00:46:54.560
So that I leave to
you to think about.

00:46:54.560 --> 00:46:59.200
That's when you have
discrete outcome case.

00:46:59.200 --> 00:47:00.900
But when you
construct a portfolio,

00:47:00.900 --> 00:47:02.800
this leads to the next question.

00:47:02.800 --> 00:47:08.240
It's in addition to the
efficient frontier discussion,

00:47:08.240 --> 00:47:11.000
is that really all
about asset allocation?

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:14.830
Is that how we calculate
our weights of each asset

00:47:14.830 --> 00:47:17.270
or strategy to choose from?

00:47:17.270 --> 00:47:19.080
The answer is no, right?

00:47:19.080 --> 00:47:22.765
So let's look at a
60/40 portfolio example.

00:47:42.800 --> 00:47:44.220
So again, two asset stock.

00:47:46.780 --> 00:47:56.150
Stock is, let's say,
60% percent, 40% bonds.

00:48:06.570 --> 00:48:31.280
So on this-- so typically
your stock volatility

00:48:31.280 --> 00:48:35.190
is higher than the bonds, and
the return, expected return,

00:48:35.190 --> 00:48:36.530
is also higher.

00:48:36.530 --> 00:48:41.770
So your 60/40 combinations
likely fall on the higher

00:48:41.770 --> 00:48:45.070
return and the higher
standard deviation

00:48:45.070 --> 00:48:48.500
part of the efficient frontier.

00:48:48.500 --> 00:48:50.760
So the question was--
so that's typically

00:48:50.760 --> 00:48:52.920
what people do before 2000.

00:48:52.920 --> 00:48:56.470
A real asset manager, the
easiest way or the passive way

00:48:56.470 --> 00:49:00.100
is just to allocate 60/40.

00:49:00.100 --> 00:49:05.600
But after 2000, what happened
was when after the equity

00:49:05.600 --> 00:49:12.750
market peaked and the bond had
a huge rally as first Greenspan

00:49:12.750 --> 00:49:20.150
cut interest rates before
the Y2K in the year 2000.

00:49:20.150 --> 00:49:22.900
You think it's kind of funny,
but at that time everybody

00:49:22.900 --> 00:49:25.210
worried about the year 2000.

00:49:25.210 --> 00:49:27.490
All the computers
are going to stop

00:49:27.490 --> 00:49:32.740
working because old software
were not prepared for crossing

00:49:32.740 --> 00:49:34.920
this millennium event.

00:49:34.920 --> 00:49:37.660
So they had to cut interest
rates for this event.

00:49:37.660 --> 00:49:41.060
But actually nothing happened,
so everything was OK.

00:49:41.060 --> 00:49:43.860
But that left the market
with plenty of cash,

00:49:43.860 --> 00:49:46.960
and also after the
tech bubble burst.

00:49:46.960 --> 00:49:50.650
So that was a good
portfolio, but then obviously

00:49:50.650 --> 00:49:54.300
in 2008 when the
equity market crashed,

00:49:54.300 --> 00:49:57.040
the bond market, the
government bond hybrid market,

00:49:57.040 --> 00:49:58.240
had a huge rally.

00:49:58.240 --> 00:50:03.610
And so that made
people question that.

00:50:03.610 --> 00:50:09.890
Is this 60/40 allocation of
asset simply by the market

00:50:09.890 --> 00:50:12.240
value the optimal
way of doing it,

00:50:12.240 --> 00:50:15.910
even though you are falling
on the Efficient Frontier?

00:50:15.910 --> 00:50:18.420
But how do you compare
different points?

00:50:18.420 --> 00:50:22.870
Is that simple choice of your
objectives, your situation,

00:50:22.870 --> 00:50:28.070
or there's actually other
ways to optimize it.

00:50:28.070 --> 00:50:32.290
So that's where the risk
parity concept was really--

00:50:32.290 --> 00:50:34.340
the concept has been
around, but the term

00:50:34.340 --> 00:50:39.210
was really coined in
2005, so quite recently,

00:50:39.210 --> 00:50:41.940
by a guy named Edward Qian.

00:50:41.940 --> 00:50:46.840
He basically said, OK,
instead of allocating 60/40

00:50:46.840 --> 00:50:49.870
based on market value,
why shouldn't we

00:50:49.870 --> 00:50:52.060
consider allocating risk?

00:50:52.060 --> 00:50:55.070
Instead of targeting a return,
targeting asset amount--

00:50:55.070 --> 00:50:58.020
let's think about
a case where we

00:50:58.020 --> 00:51:02.270
can have equal weighting of
risk between the two assets.

00:51:02.270 --> 00:51:06.780
So risk parity really means
equal risk weighting rather

00:51:06.780 --> 00:51:09.650
than equal market exposure.

00:51:09.650 --> 00:51:17.250
And then the further step
he took was he said, OK.

00:51:17.250 --> 00:51:19.980
So this actually,
OK, is equal risk.

00:51:19.980 --> 00:51:24.619
So you have lower return
and a lower risk, a lower

00:51:24.619 --> 00:51:25.410
standard deviation.

00:51:25.410 --> 00:51:29.040
But sometimes you will really
want a higher return, right?

00:51:29.040 --> 00:51:31.570
How do you satisfy both?

00:51:31.570 --> 00:51:36.060
Higher return and lower risk.

00:51:36.060 --> 00:51:37.460
Is there a free lunch?

00:51:37.460 --> 00:51:39.850
So he was thinking, right?

00:51:39.850 --> 00:51:42.370
There is, actually.

00:51:42.370 --> 00:51:45.366
It's not quite free, but
it's the closest thing.

00:51:45.366 --> 00:51:47.240
You've probably heard
this phrase many times.

00:51:47.240 --> 00:51:50.770
The closest thing in
investment to a free lunch

00:51:50.770 --> 00:51:55.430
is diversification.

00:51:55.430 --> 00:52:00.720
OK, and so he's using a
leverage here as well.

00:52:00.720 --> 00:52:03.540
let me talk about it a bit
more, about diversification,

00:52:03.540 --> 00:52:07.330
give you a couple
more examples, OK?

00:52:07.330 --> 00:52:11.230
That phrase about the free
lunch and diversification

00:52:11.230 --> 00:52:14.850
was actually from-- was
that from Markowitz?

00:52:14.850 --> 00:52:18.620
Or people gave him that term.

00:52:18.620 --> 00:52:19.800
OK, but anyway.

00:52:19.800 --> 00:52:24.690
So let me give you another
simple example, OK?

00:52:24.690 --> 00:52:34.840
So let's consider two
assets, A and B. In year one,

00:52:34.840 --> 00:52:39.970
A goes up to-- it
basically doubles.

00:52:39.970 --> 00:52:44.730
And in year two,
it goes down 50%.

00:52:44.730 --> 00:52:46.334
So where does it end up?

00:52:58.530 --> 00:53:00.160
So it started with 100%.

00:53:00.160 --> 00:53:04.250
It goes up to 200%.

00:53:04.250 --> 00:53:10.010
Then it goes down
50% on the new base,

00:53:10.010 --> 00:53:11.650
so it returns nothing, right?

00:53:11.650 --> 00:53:12.930
It comes back.

00:53:12.930 --> 00:53:21.750
So asset B in year one loses
50%, then doubles, up 100%

00:53:21.750 --> 00:53:22.930
in year two.

00:53:22.930 --> 00:53:30.950
So asset B basically
goes down to 50%

00:53:30.950 --> 00:53:35.780
and it goes back up to 100%.

00:53:35.780 --> 00:53:39.200
So that's when you look
at them independently.

00:53:39.200 --> 00:53:44.170
But what if you had a 50/50
weight of the two assets?

00:53:44.170 --> 00:53:46.600
So if someone who is
quick on math can tell me,

00:53:46.600 --> 00:53:49.240
what does it change?

00:53:49.240 --> 00:53:53.450
So A goes up like that,
B goes down like that.

00:53:53.450 --> 00:53:59.010
Now you have a 50/50 A and
B. So let's look at magic.

00:53:59.010 --> 00:54:05.520
So in year one, A,
you have only 50%.

00:54:08.050 --> 00:54:10.320
So it goes up 100%.

00:54:12.890 --> 00:54:17.320
So that's up 50%
on the total basis.

00:54:17.320 --> 00:54:25.240
B, you'll also weight
50%, but it goes down 50%.

00:54:25.240 --> 00:54:29.150
So you have lost 25%.

00:54:29.150 --> 00:54:31.340
So at the end of
year one, you're

00:54:31.340 --> 00:54:38.620
actually-- so this is a combined
50/50 portfolio, year one

00:54:38.620 --> 00:54:39.480
and year two.

00:54:39.480 --> 00:54:41.990
So you started with 100.

00:54:41.990 --> 00:54:48.850
You're up to 1.25
at this point, OK?

00:54:48.850 --> 00:54:52.600
So at the end of year
one, you rebalance, right?

00:54:52.600 --> 00:54:55.150
So you have to
come back to 50/50.

00:54:55.150 --> 00:54:56.580
So what do you do?

00:54:56.580 --> 00:55:01.780
So this becomes 75, right?

00:55:01.780 --> 00:55:05.350
So you no longer have
the 50/50 weight equal.

00:55:05.350 --> 00:55:08.750
So you have to sell
A to come back to 50

00:55:08.750 --> 00:55:11.810
and use the money to buy B.

00:55:11.810 --> 00:55:17.670
So you have a new 50/50
percent weight asset.

00:55:17.670 --> 00:55:19.570
Again, you can
figure out the math.

00:55:19.570 --> 00:55:23.800
But what happens in
the following year

00:55:23.800 --> 00:55:27.450
when you have this move,
this comes back 50%,

00:55:27.450 --> 00:55:29.230
this goes up 100%.

00:55:29.230 --> 00:55:36.740
You return another 25%
positively without volatility.

00:55:39.420 --> 00:55:40.910
So you have a straight line.

00:55:40.910 --> 00:55:43.850
You can keep-- so
this two year is

00:55:43.850 --> 00:55:48.560
a-- so that's so-called
diversification benefit.

00:55:48.560 --> 00:55:53.120
And in the 60/40 bond market,
that's really the idea

00:55:53.120 --> 00:55:56.670
people think about
how to combine them.

00:55:56.670 --> 00:56:00.900
And so let me talk a little
bit about risk parity

00:56:00.900 --> 00:56:02.370
and how you actually
achieve them.

00:56:06.050 --> 00:56:09.380
I'll try to leave plenty
of time for questions.

00:56:12.070 --> 00:56:17.510
So that's the return, and
so let's forget about these.

00:56:24.330 --> 00:56:27.260
So let's leave cash here, OK?

00:56:27.260 --> 00:56:35.900
So the previous example I gave
you, when you have two assets,

00:56:35.900 --> 00:56:43.170
one is cash, R_1,
the other is not.

00:56:43.170 --> 00:56:45.070
The other has a
volatility of sigma_2.

00:56:48.100 --> 00:56:49.820
You have this point, right?

00:56:49.820 --> 00:56:52.960
So and I said,
what's in between?

00:56:52.960 --> 00:56:54.510
It's a straight line.

00:56:54.510 --> 00:56:57.870
That's your asset allocation,
different combination.

00:57:00.800 --> 00:57:04.350
Did it occur to you, why
can't we go beyond this point?

00:57:08.230 --> 00:57:16.590
So this point is when we weight
w_2 equal to 1, w_1 equal to 0.

00:57:16.590 --> 00:57:21.570
That's when you weight
everything into the asset two.

00:57:21.570 --> 00:57:22.940
What if you go beyond that?

00:57:22.940 --> 00:57:24.060
What does that mean?

00:57:24.060 --> 00:57:24.750
OK.

