01:15:30.420 --> 01:15:34.310
So now the question
is, does that

01:15:34.310 --> 01:15:39.070
prove the risk parity approach
wrong, or does it prove right?

01:15:39.070 --> 01:15:42.040
Does the financial
crisis of 2008

01:15:42.040 --> 01:15:46.020
prove the risk parity
approach a superior approach,

01:15:46.020 --> 01:15:48.925
or does the June/May
experience prove this

01:15:48.925 --> 01:15:53.640
as the less-favored approach?

01:15:53.640 --> 01:15:55.870
What does it tell us?

01:15:55.870 --> 01:15:56.980
Think about it.

01:15:56.980 --> 01:16:00.710
So it really is inconclusive.

01:16:00.710 --> 01:16:05.380
So you observe, you extrapolate
from your historical data.

01:16:05.380 --> 01:16:10.020
But what you are
really doing is you're

01:16:10.020 --> 01:16:15.870
trying to forecast volatility,
forecast return, forecast

01:16:15.870 --> 01:16:20.120
correlation, all based
on historical data.

01:16:20.120 --> 01:16:22.790
It's like-- a lot of
people use that example.

01:16:22.790 --> 01:16:27.900
It's like driving by looking
at the rear view mirror.

01:16:27.900 --> 01:16:29.750
That's the only thing
you look at, right?

01:16:29.750 --> 01:16:33.010
You don't know what's going
on, happening in front of you.

01:16:33.010 --> 01:16:34.345
You have another question?

01:16:34.345 --> 01:16:36.520
AUDIENCE: Given all
this new information,

01:16:36.520 --> 01:16:38.220
do you find that
people are still

01:16:38.220 --> 01:16:43.170
playing similar [INAUDIBLE]
strategy with portfolio

01:16:43.170 --> 01:16:44.590
management?

01:16:44.590 --> 01:16:46.920
PROFESSOR: Very much true.

01:16:46.920 --> 01:16:47.480
Why?

01:16:47.480 --> 01:16:51.150
Right, so you said, people
should be smarter than that.

01:16:51.150 --> 01:16:55.350
It's very difficult to
discover new asset classes.

01:16:55.350 --> 01:16:58.400
It's also very
difficult to invent

01:16:58.400 --> 01:17:02.780
new strategies in which you have
a better winning probability.

01:17:02.780 --> 01:17:05.670
The other risk, the other
very interesting phenomenon,

01:17:05.670 --> 01:17:08.895
is most of the traders and
the portfolio managers,

01:17:08.895 --> 01:17:12.300
the investors, they
are career investors--

01:17:12.300 --> 01:17:16.460
meaning just like if
I'm a baseball coach,

01:17:16.460 --> 01:17:21.460
I'm hired to coach
a baseball team.

01:17:21.460 --> 01:17:23.300
My performance is
really measured

01:17:23.300 --> 01:17:27.410
against the other teams
when I win or lose, right?

01:17:27.410 --> 01:17:30.470
A portfolio manager
or investor is also

01:17:30.470 --> 01:17:32.460
measured against their peers.

01:17:32.460 --> 01:17:37.990
So the safest way for them to
do is to benchmark to an index,

01:17:37.990 --> 01:17:39.260
to the herd.

01:17:39.260 --> 01:17:43.720
So there's very little
incentive for them to get out

01:17:43.720 --> 01:17:47.080
of the crowd, because
if they are wrong,

01:17:47.080 --> 01:17:48.550
they get killed first.

01:17:48.550 --> 01:17:49.910
They lose their jobs.

01:17:49.910 --> 01:17:53.760
So the tendency is to
stay with the crowd.

01:17:53.760 --> 01:17:55.110
It's for survival instinct.

01:17:55.110 --> 01:17:57.550
It's, again, the other example.

01:17:57.550 --> 01:17:59.410
It's actually the
optimal strategy

01:17:59.410 --> 01:18:04.290
for individual portfolio manager
is really to do the same thing

01:18:04.290 --> 01:18:06.850
as other people are
doing because you

01:18:06.850 --> 01:18:10.430
stay with the force.

01:18:10.430 --> 01:18:16.217
AUDIENCE: So you said given
that we have all these groups,

01:18:16.217 --> 01:18:18.672
in the end, it's not just
that we could leave it

01:18:18.672 --> 01:18:19.654
to the computers.

01:18:19.654 --> 01:18:20.940
We need managers.

01:18:20.940 --> 01:18:23.680
So what different
are the managers

01:18:23.680 --> 01:18:25.960
doing, other than [INAUDIBLE]?

01:18:25.960 --> 01:18:28.550
PROFESSOR: Can you try to
answer that question yourself?

01:18:28.550 --> 01:18:31.440
What's the difference between
a human and a computer?

01:18:31.440 --> 01:18:35.610
That's really-- what
can human add value

01:18:35.610 --> 01:18:37.940
to what a computer can do?

01:18:37.940 --> 01:18:41.910
AUDIENCE: Consider the factors,
the market factors and news

01:18:41.910 --> 01:18:43.230
and what's going on.

01:18:43.230 --> 01:18:45.340
PROFESSOR: So taking more
information, processing

01:18:45.340 --> 01:18:51.010
information, make a judgment
on a more holistic approach.

01:18:51.010 --> 01:18:52.730
So it's an interesting question.

01:18:52.730 --> 01:18:56.500
I have to say that
computers are beating

01:18:56.500 --> 01:18:59.310
humans in many different ways.

01:18:59.310 --> 01:19:04.105
Can a computer ever get to
the point actually beating

01:19:04.105 --> 01:19:06.080
a human in investment?

01:19:06.080 --> 01:19:10.780
I can't confidently tell you
that it's not going to happen.

01:19:10.780 --> 01:19:12.640
It may happen.

01:19:12.640 --> 01:19:13.500
So I don't know.

01:19:18.987 --> 01:19:19.820
Any other questions?

01:19:19.820 --> 01:19:20.318
Yeah?

01:19:20.318 --> 01:19:21.568
AUDIENCE: Just to add to that.

01:19:21.568 --> 01:19:25.316
I think there is some more to
management than just investing.

01:19:25.316 --> 01:19:33.066
I think managers also have key
roles in their HR, key roles in

01:19:33.066 --> 01:19:35.190
just like managing people
and ensuring that they're

01:19:35.190 --> 01:19:37.790
maximizing their
talents, not just like,

01:19:37.790 --> 01:19:39.640
oh, how much money did you make?

01:19:39.640 --> 01:19:42.540
But I mean, are you moving
forward in your career

01:19:42.540 --> 01:19:43.400
while you're there?

01:19:43.400 --> 01:19:46.267
So I think management has a
role to play in that as well,

01:19:46.267 --> 01:19:47.100
not just investment.

01:19:49.830 --> 01:19:52.730
PROFESSOR: Yeah, I think
that's a good point.

01:19:52.730 --> 01:19:55.300
Yeah.

01:19:55.300 --> 01:19:57.120
All right, so-- oh, sure.

01:19:57.120 --> 01:19:57.620
Jesse?

01:19:57.620 --> 01:19:59.440
AUDIENCE: What is your
portfolio breakdown?

01:19:59.440 --> 01:20:01.960
PROFESSOR: My
personal portfolio?

01:20:01.960 --> 01:20:04.900
Well, I am actually very
conservative at this point,

01:20:04.900 --> 01:20:10.820
because if you look at my curve
of those spending and earning

01:20:10.820 --> 01:20:16.520
curve, I'm basically trying
to protect principals rather

01:20:16.520 --> 01:20:19.570
than try to maximize
return at this point.

01:20:19.570 --> 01:20:25.480
So I would be sliding down
more towards this part

01:20:25.480 --> 01:20:29.500
rather than try to go
to this corner, yeah.

01:20:29.500 --> 01:20:32.110
So I haven't really
talked much about risk.

01:20:32.110 --> 01:20:33.580
What is risk, right?

01:20:33.580 --> 01:20:37.500
So I talk about volatility
or standard deviation.

01:20:37.500 --> 01:20:41.200
But as we all know that, as
Peter mentioned last time as

01:20:41.200 --> 01:20:46.550
well, there are many other ways
to look at risk-- value at risk

01:20:46.550 --> 01:20:51.290
or half distribution or
truncated distribution,

01:20:51.290 --> 01:20:55.160
or simply maximum loss you
can afford to take, right?

01:20:58.500 --> 01:21:01.660
But looking at standard
deviation or volatility

01:21:01.660 --> 01:21:02.680
is an elegant way.

01:21:02.680 --> 01:21:04.310
You can see.

01:21:04.310 --> 01:21:09.170
I can really show you in
very simple math about how

01:21:09.170 --> 01:21:11.440
the concept actually plays out.

01:21:11.440 --> 01:21:14.600
But in the end,
actually volatility

01:21:14.600 --> 01:21:18.420
is really not the best
measure, in my view, of risk.

01:21:18.420 --> 01:21:18.920
Why?

01:21:18.920 --> 01:21:24.368
Let me give you another simple
example before we leave.

01:21:28.670 --> 01:21:31.450
So let's say this is over time.

01:21:34.400 --> 01:21:43.700
This is your cumulative
return or you dollar amount.

01:21:43.700 --> 01:21:46.090
So you start from here.

01:21:46.090 --> 01:21:53.489
If you go flat,
then-- does anyone

01:21:53.489 --> 01:21:55.155
like to have this
kind of a performance?

01:21:58.300 --> 01:21:59.230
Right?

01:21:59.230 --> 01:22:00.410
Of course, right?

01:22:00.410 --> 01:22:01.240
This is very nice.

01:22:01.240 --> 01:22:02.190
You keep going up.

01:22:02.190 --> 01:22:03.930
You never go down.

01:22:03.930 --> 01:22:08.940
But what's the
volatility of that?

01:22:08.940 --> 01:22:12.890
The volatility is
probably not low, right?

01:22:12.890 --> 01:22:16.345
And then on the
other hand, you could

01:22:16.345 --> 01:22:26.840
have-- what I'm
trying to say, when

01:22:26.840 --> 01:22:30.010
you look at expected
return matching expected

01:22:30.010 --> 01:22:38.190
return and the volatility,
you can still really not

01:22:38.190 --> 01:22:40.630
selecting the best combination.

01:22:40.630 --> 01:22:43.530
Because what you really
should care about

01:22:43.530 --> 01:22:46.540
is not just your volatility.

01:22:46.540 --> 01:22:51.820
And again, bear in mind all
the discussion about the Modern

01:22:51.820 --> 01:22:54.920
Portfolio Theory is based
on one key assumption here.

01:22:54.920 --> 01:22:59.220
It's about Gaussian
distribution, OK?

01:22:59.220 --> 01:23:01.240
Normal distribution.

01:23:01.240 --> 01:23:04.800
The two parameters, mean
and standard deviation,

01:23:04.800 --> 01:23:06.850
categorize the distribution.

01:23:06.850 --> 01:23:11.780
But in reality, you have many
other sets of distributions.

01:23:11.780 --> 01:23:17.400
And so it's a concept
still up for a lot

01:23:17.400 --> 01:23:19.460
of discussion and debate.

01:23:19.460 --> 01:23:24.710
But I want to leave
that with you as well.

01:23:24.710 --> 01:23:25.690
Yeah?

01:23:25.690 --> 01:23:28.385
AUDIENCE: Just going back to
the same question about what

01:23:28.385 --> 01:23:30.590
these guys were asking
about management

01:23:30.590 --> 01:23:33.060
and how do they add
value, I think the people

01:23:33.060 --> 01:23:35.170
who added value-- there
were some people who

01:23:35.170 --> 01:23:38.430
added a tremendous amount of
value in the financial crisis.

01:23:38.430 --> 01:23:40.400
And they were doing
the same mathematics.

01:23:40.400 --> 01:23:42.455
But a difference was in
their expected return

01:23:42.455 --> 01:23:44.910
of various assets was
different from the entire--

01:23:44.910 --> 01:23:46.360
the broad market.

01:23:46.360 --> 01:23:50.500
So if you can just know what
expected return is that,

01:23:50.500 --> 01:23:52.810
probably that is the only
answer to the whole portfolio

01:23:52.810 --> 01:23:53.590
management debate.

01:23:53.590 --> 01:23:54.370
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:23:54.370 --> 01:24:00.900
If you can forecast expected
return, then that's-- yeah,

01:24:00.900 --> 01:24:01.920
now you know the game.

01:24:01.920 --> 01:24:02.760
You solved it.

01:24:02.760 --> 01:24:04.605
You solved the big
part of the puzzle.

01:24:04.605 --> 01:24:05.105
Yeah?

01:24:05.105 --> 01:24:07.250
AUDIENCE: What
management does is

01:24:07.250 --> 01:24:10.370
how good it can do [INAUDIBLE]
expected return, full stop.

01:24:10.370 --> 01:24:10.980
Nothing more.

01:24:14.200 --> 01:24:15.470
PROFESSOR: I disagree on that.

01:24:15.470 --> 01:24:16.490
That's the only thing.

01:24:16.490 --> 01:24:21.040
Because given two managers, they
have the same expected return,

01:24:21.040 --> 01:24:24.710
but you can still further
differentiate them, right?

01:24:24.710 --> 01:24:25.650
So that's-- yeah.

01:24:25.650 --> 01:24:29.500
And that's what all this
discussion is about.

01:24:29.500 --> 01:24:33.940
But yes, expected return will
drive lot of these decisions.

01:24:33.940 --> 01:24:37.530
If you know one manager's good
expected return, three years

01:24:37.530 --> 01:24:41.122
later, he's going to make 150%.

01:24:41.122 --> 01:24:43.080
You don't really care
what's in between, right?

01:24:43.080 --> 01:24:45.140
You're just going
to ride it through.

01:24:45.140 --> 01:24:48.840
But the problem is you
don't know for sure.

01:24:48.840 --> 01:24:52.287
You will never be sure.

01:24:52.287 --> 01:24:53.870
AUDIENCE: I'd like
to comment on that.

01:24:53.870 --> 01:24:54.220
PROFESSOR: Sure.

01:24:54.220 --> 01:24:55.595
AUDIENCE: What
[INAUDIBLE] looked

01:24:55.595 --> 01:24:58.330
at in simplified
settings, estimating

01:24:58.330 --> 01:25:00.560
returns and volatilities.

01:25:00.560 --> 01:25:04.820
And the problem, the
conclusion for the problem,

01:25:04.820 --> 01:25:09.770
was basically cannot
estimate returns very well,

01:25:09.770 --> 01:25:12.240
even with more data,
over a historical period.

01:25:12.240 --> 01:25:15.950
But you can estimate volatility
much better with more data.

01:25:15.950 --> 01:25:19.060
So there's really an
issue of perhaps luck

01:25:19.060 --> 01:25:23.160
in getting the return estimates
right with different managers,

01:25:23.160 --> 01:25:26.480
which are hard to prove
that there was really

01:25:26.480 --> 01:25:28.580
an expertise behind that.

01:25:28.580 --> 01:25:33.910
Although with volatility, you
can have improved estimates.

01:25:33.910 --> 01:25:37.290
And I think possibly with
a risk parity portfolio,

01:25:37.290 --> 01:25:40.750
those portfolios are focusing
not on return expectations,

01:25:40.750 --> 01:25:43.870
but saying if we're going to
consider different choices

01:25:43.870 --> 01:25:46.560
based on just how
much risk they have

01:25:46.560 --> 01:25:51.400
and equalize that risk, then
the expected return should

01:25:51.400 --> 01:25:54.116
be comparable across
those, perhaps.

01:25:54.116 --> 01:25:55.800
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:25:55.800 --> 01:25:57.290
So that highlights
the difficulty

01:25:57.290 --> 01:25:59.840
of forecasting return,
forecasting volatility,

01:25:59.840 --> 01:26:01.440
forecasting correlation.

01:26:01.440 --> 01:26:04.780
So risk parity appears
to be another elegant way

01:26:04.780 --> 01:26:07.800
of proposing the
optimal strategy

01:26:07.800 --> 01:26:10.122
but it has the same problems.

01:26:10.122 --> 01:26:10.782
Yeah?

01:26:10.782 --> 01:26:12.740
AUDIENCE: Actually, I
also wanted to highlight.

01:26:12.740 --> 01:26:14.930
You mentioned the
Kelly criterion,

01:26:14.930 --> 01:26:18.470
which we haven't covered the
theory for that previously.

01:26:18.470 --> 01:26:21.100
But I encourage people
to look into that.

01:26:21.100 --> 01:26:24.840
It deals with issues of
multi-period investments

01:26:24.840 --> 01:26:26.830
as opposed to
single-period investments.

01:26:26.830 --> 01:26:30.945
And most-- all this classical
theory we've been discussing,

01:26:30.945 --> 01:26:34.600
or that I discuss, covers
just a single period analysis,

01:26:34.600 --> 01:26:38.020
which is an oversimplification
of an investment.

01:26:38.020 --> 01:26:41.952
And when you are investing
over multiple periods,

01:26:41.952 --> 01:26:45.790
the Kelly criterion tells you
how to optimally basically

01:26:45.790 --> 01:26:47.780
bet with your bank roll.

01:26:47.780 --> 01:26:53.380
And actually there's an
excellent book, at least

01:26:53.380 --> 01:26:56.120
I like it, called
Fortune's Formula

01:26:56.120 --> 01:26:58.510
that talks about--
[? we already ?]

01:26:58.510 --> 01:27:00.830
said the origins of
options theory in finance.

01:27:00.830 --> 01:27:02.760
But it does get into
the Kelly criterion.

01:27:02.760 --> 01:27:08.780
And there was a rather major
discussion between Shannon,

01:27:08.780 --> 01:27:12.280
a mathematician at MIT, who
advocated applying the Kelly

01:27:12.280 --> 01:27:17.139
criterion, and Paul Samuelson,
one of the major economists.

01:27:17.139 --> 01:27:18.180
PROFESSOR: Also from MIT.

01:27:18.180 --> 01:27:19.790
AUDIENCE: Also from MIT.

01:27:19.790 --> 01:27:23.710
And there was a great
dispute about how you should

01:27:23.710 --> 01:27:26.339
do portfolio optimization.

01:27:26.339 --> 01:27:27.630
PROFESSOR: That's a great book.

01:27:27.630 --> 01:27:30.090
And a lot of
characters in that book

01:27:30.090 --> 01:27:34.840
actually are from MIT--
and Ed Thorp, for example.

01:27:34.840 --> 01:27:41.530
And it's really about people
trying to find the Holy Grail

01:27:41.530 --> 01:27:44.540
magic formula-- not
really to that extent,

01:27:44.540 --> 01:27:47.910
but finding something other
people haven't figured out.

01:27:47.910 --> 01:27:50.900
But it's very
interesting history.

01:27:50.900 --> 01:27:56.830
Big names like Shannon, very
successful in other fields.

01:27:56.830 --> 01:28:01.000
In his later part of his
career and life really devoted

01:28:01.000 --> 01:28:06.915
most of his time to
studying this problem.

01:28:06.915 --> 01:28:08.710
You know Shannon, right?

01:28:08.710 --> 01:28:09.940
Claude Shannon?

01:28:09.940 --> 01:28:15.270
He's the father of
information theory

01:28:15.270 --> 01:28:18.520
and has a lot to do with
the later information age

01:28:18.520 --> 01:28:23.540
invention of computers
and very successful, yeah.

